## Virtual SD Card Suppression

The emulator attaches a virtio-blk device (`vde`) for the SD card regardless of `hw.sdCard=no` in the AVD config. The vendor fstab (`/vendor/etc/fstab.ranchu`) contains a `voldmanaged=sdcard:auto` entry mapping this device, causing vold to claim it as a managed disk. Since the filesystem is unrecognized, vold posts an "Unsupported Virtual SD card" notification.

### Why simpler approaches don't work

- `hw.sdCard=no` / `sdcard.size=0` — controls the SD card _image_, not the virtio device slot
- No `--no-sdcard` emulator flag exists
- `/vendor` is a read-only dm logical partition (can't remount rw to edit fstab)
- `sm set-virtual-disk false` — targets a different mechanism (StorageManagerService loop device)
- Runtime `service call notification` to cancel — NMS persists the notification and no cancel API works on this build
- Ramdisk `overlay.d/init.*.rc` approach — works on cold boot but not on `adb reboot`

### The fix: Magisk `post-fs-data.d` script

A shell script pushed to `/data/adb/post-fs-data.d/disable-sdcard.sh` runs on every boot (including `adb reboot`). It parses the vendor fstab to find the sdcard device name, resolves its backing virtio device via sysfs, and unbinds it from `virtio_blk`.

**Why this timing works:** Android init triggers `post-fs-data` before `class_start core` (which starts vold). By the time vold reads the fstab, the block device no longer exists.

### Useful diagnostic commands

```bash
adb shell sm list-disks                          # vold's disk list (empty = fix working)
adb shell su -c 'cat /vendor/etc/fstab.ranchu'   # the voldmanaged=sdcard entry
adb shell su -c 'cat /proc/partitions'            # all block devices (vda-vde)
adb shell su -c 'readlink /sys/dev/block/MAJ:MIN' # resolve block device to virtio device
```

### Emulator block device layout (API 29, arm64-v8a)

| Device | Major:Minor | Size   | Purpose                      |
| ------ | ----------- | ------ | ---------------------------- |
| vda    | 254,0       | ~2.3GB | super (system+vendor via dm) |
| vdb    | 254,16      | ~66MB  | cache                        |
| vdc    | 254,32      | ~6GB   | userdata (/data)             |
| vdd    | 254,48      | ~1MB   | encryption key               |
| vde    | 254,64      | ~59MB  | SD card (the culprit)        |

## Emulator Flags

`-no-boot-anim -no-snapstorage -gpu host -no-metrics -no-location-ui -feature -Vulkan -port 5554`
Plus `-qemu -append androidboot.serialconsole=0` (must be last — everything after `-qemu` goes to QEMU).

## Module Output

- `home.packages` — `pkgs.rclone` (host-side WebDAV server) + `androidScript` (the `android` command)
- `android-sdk` — SDK packages via `android-nixpkgs`
- `targets.darwin.defaults` — Emulator app preferences (dark theme, forward shortcuts, disable crash reports)

## Gotchas / Lessons Learned

- `--daemon` mode on rclone mount via `adb shell` hangs the parent terminal. Use `</dev/null >/dev/null 2>&1 &` instead.
- `--allow-non-empty` on rclone mount masks errors when stale mounts exist. Better to error out and let the cleanup handle it.
- Log files under `/data/local/tmp/` are owned by root (created via `su`). Reading requires `adb shell su -c 'cat ...'`.
- `adb` commands need `-s emulator-5554` when multiple devices are connected. The `adb` variable bakes this in.
- The emulator port is pinned to 5554 so the ADB serial (`emulator-5554`) is deterministic.
- `rclone serve webdav` and `rclone mount` both need `--config=""` to suppress "config not found" notices.
- `hw.sdCard=no` does NOT prevent the emulator from attaching a virtio-blk SD card device. The notification comes from vold reading the vendor fstab, not from the AVD config.
- `/vendor` is a read-only logical dm partition from the super device — `mount -o remount,rw /vendor` fails even with Magisk root.
- `adb shell "[ -f /data/adb/... ]"` always fails — the shell user can't read `/data/adb/`. Use `adb shell "su -c '[ -f /data/adb/... ]'"` instead.
